Data Cleaning and Exploration

# Clean and Setup Data --------------------------------------------------------

claims <- read_csv("raw_data/insurance_claims.csv") %>% 
  select(-"_c39", -policy_number, -incident_location, -insured_zip) %>% 
  #because the variable _c39 has no variation and policy no is irrelevant
  mutate(
    # insured_zip = as.factor(insured_zip), # zip, loc, policy are categorical
    # and need to be stored as strings but i decided not to include them bcuz
    # there is no more than one claim for a given policy and very few for given
    # zip and incident location (remember only 1000 obs in total)
    fraud_reported = as.numeric(fraud_reported=="Y")) # want 1s 0s

# Split -----------------------------------------------------------------------
set.seed(111)

choose_80 <- sample(1:nrow(claims), replace = FALSE, nrow(claims)*0.8)
choose_20 <- setdiff(1:nrow(claims), choose_80)

claims_80 <- claims[choose_80, ]
claims_20 <- claims[choose_20, ]
unique(claims$incident_severity)
## [1] "Major Damage"   "Minor Damage"   "Total Loss"     "Trivial Damage"
ggplot(claims, aes(incident_severity, fill=as.factor(fraud_reported))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Fraud Reported"))

# claims of major damage are more likely to be reported as fraud

ggplot(claims, aes(insured_sex, fill=as.factor(fraud_reported))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Fraud Reported"))

# claims by insured males are more likely to be fraud than claims by females

ggplot(claims, aes(insured_education_level, fill=as.factor(fraud_reported))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Fraud Reported"))

# no visible differences

ggplot(claims, aes(insured_hobbies, fill=as.factor(fraud_reported))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Fraud Reported"))

# those who include chess or cross-fit in their hobbies are more likely to 
# make a fraud claim whereas campers and golfers are not much likely

Modeling and Performance

# Linear Model ----------------------------------------------------------------

m_linear <-  lm(fraud_reported ~ ., data = claims_80)

test_preds <- select(claims_20, fraud_reported) # will store all predictions
test_preds$prob_linear <- predict(m_linear, newdata =  claims_20)
test_preds$pred_linear <- as.factor(ifelse(test_preds$prob_linear > 0.5, "1", "0"))

confusionMatrix(as.factor(test_preds$fraud_reported),
                as.factor(test_preds$pred_linear))

# Shrink ----------------------------------------------------------------------

# remember the model.matrix function we used before in previous assignment
# it is an easy way to convert categorical variables into a bunch of dummies
X80 <- model.matrix(fraud_reported ~ ., claims_80)  
y80 <- as.numeric(claims_80$fraud_reported)

X20 <- model.matrix(fraud_reported ~ ., claims_20)  
y20 <- as.numeric(claims_20$fraud_reported)

# 
lambda_grid <- 10^seq(2, -4, by = -.1) 
m_ridge <- glmnet(X80, y80, alpha = 0, lambda = lambda_grid)
cv_ridge <- cv.glmnet(X80, y80, alpha = 0, lambda = lambda_grid)
plot(cv_ridge)

ridge_star <- cv_ridge$lambda.min

# Performance
test_preds$prob_ridge <- predict(m_ridge, s = ridge_star, newx = X20)
test_preds$pred_ridge <- as.factor(ifelse(test_preds$prob_ridge > 0.5, "1", "0"))

confusionMatrix(as.factor(test_preds$fraud_reported),
                as.factor(test_preds$pred_ridge))

# Best Boosting ---------------------------------------------------------------

# to find the best boosting model for out of sample accuracy, i followed this
# youtube video: https://youtu.be/woVTNwRrFHE

pars_mlog <- list("objective" = "multi:softprob",
                  "eval_metric" = "mlogloss",
                  "num_class" = nc)

train_matrix <- xgb.DMatrix(data = X80, label = y80)
test_matrix  <- xgb.DMatrix(data = X20, label = y20)

watchlist <- list(train = train_matrix, test = test_matrix)

bst_model <- xgb.train(params = pars_mlog,
                       data = train_matrix,
                       nrounds = 500,
                       watchlist = watchlist,
                       eta = 0.01, max.depth = 3, gamma = 0)
